  "chunk_index": 19,
  "summary": "Following the identification of a corpse in the Bateswick Apartments, news reveals that the body previously thought to be Mabel Sainsbury-Sil is actually Mrs. Albert Chapman. Mr. Lestrade of 58 Charlotte Street confirmed this identity by matching the deceased's teeth and jawbone to records from the late Mr. Morley. Although Mabel Sainsbury-Sil's clothes and handbag were found with the body, she remains missing.\n\nInspector Japp discusses the case with Hercule Poirot, noting that the corpse was likely mutilated to disguise its identity. Poirot explains that the confusion arose because both women were in their forties and had dyed blonde hair. Japp suggests a new theory: that Mabel Sainsbury-Sil may have killed Mrs. Chapman, rather than the other way around.\n\nJapp later informs Poirot that the official investigation has been abruptly canceled by orders from the Ministry of Foreign Affairs. Japp suspects the shutdown is intended to protect the secrets of the deceased and avoid political complications for Mrs. Chapman's husband, who may hold a sensitive overseas position. Despite this, Poirot vows to continue his own investigation.\n\nPoirot receives a letter from Alistair Blunt requesting a meeting at his home in Chelsea. Shortly after, an unidentified woman makes a threatening phone call to Poirot, warning him not to accept any commissions related to the case and to stop interfering. She dismisses Henry Morley's death as an incidental matter. Poirot suspects the caller may be Mabel Sainsbury-Sil using a disguised voice. The following morning, news breaks that the Prime Minister narrowly escaped an assassination attempt by an Indian assailant, prompting Poirot to visit Japp at Scotland Yard.",
